PersistentVectorDB implements a Write-Ahead Log (WAL) for crash recovery, ensuring that vectors are never lost even if the process is killed mid-write. This is critical for production private deployments.

Why WAL Is Needed

Without WAL, a crash during a save operation can corrupt the database:
- Process starts writing 17,000 vectors to vectors.bin
- Power failure or OOM kill at vector 8,000
- vectors.bin now contains partial data
- On restart: database is corrupted or inconsistent with metadata.json

With WAL:
- Every insert is first written to wal.log (append-only, atomic)
- wal.log is durable before the insert is acknowledged
- On restart: replay wal.log to recover operations since last checkpoint
- Save creates a consistent snapshot, then truncates wal.log

WAL Implementation in This Codebase

```javascript
// From src/storage/persistent-vector-db.js

const WAL_OPS = {
  INSERT: 'I',     // New vector inserted
  DELETE: 'D',     // Vector deleted
  UPDATE: 'U',     // Vector updated
  CHECKPOINT: 'C'  // Snapshot saved, WAL can be truncated
};

// Each WAL entry is newline-delimited JSON
// Example wal.log content:
// {"op":"I","ts":1737849600000,"data":{"id":"doc_123","vector":[0.1,0.2,...],"metadata":{...}}}
// {"op":"I","ts":1737849601000,"data":{"id":"doc_124","vector":[...],"metadata":{...}}}
// {"op":"C","ts":1737849602000,"data":{}}  <- checkpoint
```

Storage Format (from src/storage/persistent-vector-db.js)

```
.ruvector/knowledge-base/
  ├── vectors.bin      # Raw Float32 vectors in binary (not JSON)
  ├── metadata.json    # ID index and metadata (small, queryable)
  ├── manifest.json    # Version, dimensions, vector count, stats
  ├── wal.log          # Write-ahead log (cleared after checkpoint)
  ├── vectors.bin.tmp  # Temp file during atomic save
  └── metadata.json.tmp
```

Atomic Save Pattern

```javascript
// Atomic save: write to temp, then rename (atomic on POSIX)
async save() {
  // 1. Write vectors to .tmp file
  await writeFile(paths.vectorsTemp, vectorBuffer);

  // 2. Rename: atomic on Linux/macOS (not on Windows FAT32)
  await rename(paths.vectorsTemp, paths.vectors);

  // 3. Write metadata
  await writeFile(paths.metadataTemp, JSON.stringify(metadataObj));
  await rename(paths.metadataTemp, paths.metadata);

  // 4. Checkpoint WAL (safe to truncate now)
  await writeWAL(WAL_OPS.CHECKPOINT, {});
  await truncateWAL();
}
```

Debounced Auto-Save

Saves are debounced to batch multiple inserts:

```javascript
scheduleSave() {
  this.dirty = true;
  if (this.saveTimer) clearTimeout(this.saveTimer);

  // Save 2 seconds after the last insert (configurable)
  this.saveTimer = setTimeout(() => {
    this.save().catch(err => console.error('Auto-save failed:', err));
  }, this.options.saveIntervalMs); // Default: 2000ms
}
```

This means: if you insert 500 documents rapidly, only one save occurs (2 seconds after the last insert), not 500 saves.

Manual Flush for Critical Operations

```javascript
// Force immediate save (bypasses debounce)
await db.flush();

// Also called via RuvectorStore.commit():
await ruvectorStore.commit();
// Output: "✅ Data persisted to disk (RuVector binary format)"
```

Process Exit Handling

The module registers handlers to save on clean shutdown:

```javascript
process.on('beforeExit', async () => {
  await closeAllDatabases();  // Flushes all PersistentVectorDB instances
});

process.on('SIGINT', async () => {
  await closeAllDatabases();
  process.exit(0);
});

process.on('SIGTERM', async () => {
  await closeAllDatabases();
  process.exit(0);
});
```

